The aptasensor of ITO/Au/MER/ssDNA electrode in the presence of Th-CDs-tDNA was applied for determination of cocaine using DPV technique. As the Fig. 6
                         shows, DPV responses linearly increased with the increasing cocaine concentration over the range 10–70 pM with regression equation of ip (μA) = 0.0049C[

                           cocaine

                        ]-0.0136 and a correlation coefficient of 0.995. The limit of detection (LOD) of this method was 0.26 pM (3 s). A comparison between the analytical performance of the proposed method with other techniques for detection of cocaine (Table 1
                        ) proves the high performance of the ITO/Au/MER/ssDNA electrode and Th-CDs-tDNA as a modified probe.

One other factor for a biosensor, other than high sensitivity, is its selectivity in the presence of the interferences. Here, we checked the electrochemical signal of 70 pM cocaine in presence of 100 μM of thrombin, ATP, morphine, diazepam and caffeine as some potential interferences. The results were presented in Fig. 7
                        A, which proves high selectivity of biosensor. In fact, the electrochemical signal of 70 pM cocaine, in a solution containing 100 nM of all interferences, remains almost unchanged relative to sole cocaine (less than 4 %) These results prove the feasibility of the proposed biosensors. The result of 3 measurement (Table 2
                        ) of a solutions of 50 pM of cocaine with three constructed individual sensors shows a RSD of 6 % which shows the acceptable reproducibility of the proposed sensor. The signal of 50 pM of cocaine for one electrode in 8 days was monitored to study the stability of sensor. After each measurement, the electrode was washed and put in buffer (pH = 7.4, 0.1 M phosphate). Here, as the results in Fig. 7B show, after 8 days, the sensor retains about 80% of its signal of the first day, proving the stability of the sensor.
